<tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>25975</anchor> <rss>anon.245.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Proof</taxon> <addr>anon.245</addr>  <route>anon.245.xml</route>    </frontmatter> <mainmatter>
  <p>Our construction of the <link href="jms-004G.xml" type="local" addr="jms-004G" title="The initial reflection algebra">initial reflection algebra</link> for each <tex>A: \mathcal {V}</tex> is one of several equivalent formulations of reflective subuniverse in univalent foundations.</p>
</mainmatter> <backmatter><contributions/> <context><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>25976</anchor> <rss>jms-004H.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Corollary</taxon> <addr>jms-004H</addr>  <route>jms-004H.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>3</month> <day>22</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>Impredicative subuniverses are reflective</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>If <tex>\mathcal {U} \in \mathcal {V}</tex> is an impredicative pair of universes, then <tex>\mathcal {U}</tex> is reflective in <tex>\mathcal {V}</tex>.</p>
 
   
   
 
</mainmatter> </tree></context> <related><tree expanded="false" show-heading="true" show-metadata="true" toc="false" numbered="false" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>25977</anchor> <rss>jms-004G.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Theorem</taxon> <addr>jms-004G</addr>  <route>jms-004G.xml</route> <date><year>2023</year> <month>3</month> <day>22</day></date> <authors><author><link href="jonmsterling.xml" type="local" jonmsterling="addr">Jon Sterling</link></author> </authors> <title>The initial reflection algebra</title> </frontmatter> <mainmatter><p>Let <tex>\mathcal {U} \in \mathcal {V}</tex> be an impredicative pair of universes with <tex>A: \mathcal {V}</tex>. There we may construct a  <link href="jms-003O.xml" type="local" addr="jms-003O" title="Reflection algebras and homomorphisms">reflection algebra</link> <tex>A _{ \mathcal {U} }  : { A } \downarrow { \mathcal {U} }</tex> such that for any other <link href="jms-003O.xml" type="local" addr="jms-003O" title="Reflection algebras and homomorphisms">reflection algebra</link> <tex>X: { A } \downarrow { \mathcal {U} }</tex>, the space of <link href="jms-003O.xml" type="local" addr="jms-003O" title="Reflection algebras and homomorphisms">homomorphisms</link> <tex>A _{ \mathcal {U} } \multimap  X</tex> is contractible.</p>
 
   
   <tree expanded="true" show-heading="true" show-metadata="false" toc="false" numbered="true" root="false"><frontmatter><anchor>25978</anchor> <rss>anon.246.rss.xml</rss> <taxon>Proof</taxon> <addr>anon.246</addr>  <route>anon.246.xml</route>    </frontmatter> <mainmatter>
  <p>Our <link href="jms-0044.xml" type="local" addr="jms-0044" title="Splitting the generic element of the generic cone">splitting of the generic element of the generic cone</link> <tex>{ \Delta  I } \xrightarrow {{ p }}{ 1 _{ { A } \downarrow { \mathcal {U} } } }</tex> over the identity functor on reflection algebras <link href="jms-003E.xml" type="local" addr="jms-003E" title="A wild universal cone from a splitting of the generic element">yields a new (incoherent) cone</link> <tex>{ \Delta  J } \xrightarrow {{ q }}{ 1 _{ { A } \downarrow { \mathcal {U} } } }</tex> whose generic element <tex>q _{ J } :J \multimap  J</tex> may be identified with the identity homomorphism. It <link href="jms-003B.xml" type="local" addr="jms-003B" title="Wild initial objects from universal cones">follows</link> that each  space of homomorphisms <tex>J \to  X</tex> is contractible. Therefore, we define <tex>A _{ \mathcal {U} }</tex> to be the apex <tex>J</tex>.</p>
</mainmatter> </tree>
 
